 मासान्ताः P.V.4.68 while on some ccasions a part only of it s seen repeated. The repeti- ion goes on upto a particular imit which is stated as in सिद्धवदत्राभात् P.VI.4.22, प्राग्रीश्वरान्नि- ाताः P.I.4.56. Many times the imit is not stated by the author of he Sūtras but it is understood by irtue of a counteracting word ccurring later on. On still other ccasions, thc limit is defined by he ancient traditional interpreters y means of a sort of convention hich is called स्वरितत्वप्रतिज्ञा. This धिकार or governance has its in- luence of three kinds: ( 1 ) by eing valid or present in all the ules which come under its sphere f influence, e. g. स्त्रियाम् or अङ्गस्य; 2) by showing additional pro- erties e. g. the word अपादान being pplied to cases where there is o actual separation as in सांकाश्य- ेभ्यः पाटलिपुत्रका अभिरूपतराः: (3) by howing additional force such as etting aside even subsequent rules f opposing. These three types of he influence which a word marked ith स्वरित and hence termed अधिकार ossesses are called respectively धिकारगति, अधिक क्रार्य and अधिककार. or details see M.Bh. on I.3.11. his अधिकार or governing rule xerts its influence in three ways: 1) generally by proceeding ahead n subsequent rules like the stream f a river, (2)sometimes by jumps ike a frog omitting a rule or ore, and (3)rarely by proceeding ackward with a lion's glance; cf. िंहावलोकितं चैव मण्डूकप्लुतमेव च | गड्गाप्रवा- वच्चापि अधिकारास्त्रिधा मताः ॥

