'''अनियत''' not subject to any limitation f. प्रत्यया नियताः, अर्था अनियताः, अर्था ियताः, प्रत्यया अनियताः  M.Bh. on II. .50. In the casc of नियमविधि (a res- rictive rule or statement ) a limi- ation is put on one or more of the onstituent elements or factors of hat rule, the limited element bcing alled नियत, the other one being ermcd अनेियत; also see Kāś. on I.2.30.

'''अनियतपुंसक''' whose sex-especially hether it is a male or a female-is ot definitely known from its mere ight; small insects which are so. he term क्षुद्रा in P. IV.1.131 is xplained in the Mahābhāṣya as ्षुद्रा नाम अनियतपुंसका अङगगहीना वा M. Bh. n P. IV.1.131.

'''अनिर्दिष्टार्थ''' whose sense has not been pecifically stated ; the word is sed with reference to such affixes s are not prescribed in any speci- ic sense or senses and hence as are ooked upon as possessing the sense hich the base after which they re prescribed has got: cf. अनिर्दिष्टार्थाः  ्रत्ययाः स्वार्थे भवन्ति -affixes, to which o meaning has been assigned, onvey the meaning of the bases to hich they are added; cf. Par. ek. Pari. 113; cf. also M. Bh. on II.2.4, III, 2.67, III.3.19, III. .9, VI.1.102.

'''अनिष्ट''' an undesired consequence or esult; cf. अनिष्टं च प्राप्नोति इष्टे च न सिध्यति . Bh. on I.3.1 , also cf. नानिष्टार्था ास्त्रप्रवृत्तिः M. Bh. on VI.1.2.

'''अनिष्टिज्ञ''' ignorant or inattentive to hat the Grammarian intends or esires to say. cf. तत्र सौर्यभगवतोक्तम्- निज्ञो वाडव: पठति ।  इत्यत एव चतुर्मात्रः ्लुत: M. Bh. on VIII.2.106.

'''अनीयर्''' kṛt affix, termed कृत्य also orming the pot. pass. part. of a



 oot; cf. तव्यत्तव्यानीयरः P.III.1.96. e.g. ee the forms करणीयं, हरणीयं, the mute ् showing the acute accent on the enultimate vowel,

'''अनुकरण''' (l) imitation; a word utter- d in imitation of another; an imi- ative name: cf. अनुकरणे चानितिपरम् .I.4.62; अनुकरणं हि शिष्टशिष्टाप्रतिषिद्धेषु था लौकिकवैदिकेषु, Śiva sūtra 2 Vārt 1; f. also प्रकृतिवद् अनुकरणं भवति an imi- ative name is like its original Par. ek. Pari. 36; also M.Bh. on VIII. .46; (2) imitative word, onoma- opoetic word; cf. एवं ह्याहुः कुक्कुटाः ुक्कुड् इति ।  नैवं त आहुः | अनुकरणमेतत्तेषाम् . Bh. on I.3.48. cf. also दुन्दुभि: ति शब्दानुकरणम् Nir. IX. 12.

'''अनुकर्षण''' dragging (from the preced- ng rule) to the following rule tak- ng the previous rule or a part of t as understood in the following ule or rules in order; the same as नुवृत्ति; cf. अनुकर्षणार्थश्चकारः Kāś. on II. .18, III.2.26, VII. 1.48: cf also he Paribhāṣā; चानुकृष्टं नोत्तरत्र -that hich is attracted from a preced- ng rule by the particle च is not alid in the rule that follows; Par. ek. Pari. 78.

'''अनुकृष्ट''' attracted from a previous ule as is frequently done in Pāṇi- i's rules. See the word अनुकर्षण bove.

'''अनुक्त''' not actually stated or expressed n a rule; cf. चकारोऽनुक्तसमुच्चयार्थ: āś. on II.4.18, III.2.26, VII. .48; also cf. Nyāsa on P.II.2.9 नुक्रम right or regular order in a edic recital, called क्रम. e. g. वायव: ्थ.

'''अनुक्रमण''' enumeration (in the right rder as.opposed to व्युत्क्रम ); e. g. थ किमर्थमुत्तरत्र एवमादि अनुक्रमणं क्रियते . Bh. on II.1.58; also on IV. .70; verbal forms of the root क्रम् ith अनु occur in this sense very


 requently; e.g. यदित ऊर्ध्वे अनुक्रमिष्यामः; o also the p.p.p. अनुक्रान्तं occurs requently in the same sense. नुतन्त्र lit. that which follows Tantra .e. Śāstra which means the original ules of a Śāstra; technical term for artika used by Bhartṛhari;cf. सूत्राणां ानुतन्त्राणां भाष्याणां च प्रणेतृभिः Vāk. Pad. .23, where the word अनुतन्त्र is ex- lained as Vārtika by the com- entator.

'''अनुत्तम''' other than उत्तम or the first erson; cf. विभाषितं सोपसर्गमनुत्तमम् P. II.1.53 and Kāśika thereon.

'''अनुत्पति''' non-production of an ele- ent of a word such as an affix or n augment or the like; cf. वावचने ानुत्पत्त्यर्थम् P.III.1.2 Vārt. 7, तत्रो- ्पत्तिर्वा प्रसङ्गो यथा तद्धिते P. III.1.94 ārt. 2, also कृष्यादिषु चानुत्पत्तिः (णिचः) .III.1.26, Vārt. 3.

'''अनुदात्त''' non-udatta, absence of the cute accent;one of the Bāhyapra- atnas or external efforts to pro- uce sound. This sense possibly efers to a stage or a time when nly one accent, the acute or उदात्त as recognized just as in English nd other languages at present, his udatta was given to only one owel in a single word (simple or ompound) and all the other owels were uttered accentless.i.e. नुदात्त. Possibly with this idea.in iew, the standard rule 'अनुदात्तं पदमे- वर्जम्'* was laid down by Panini. .VI.1.158. As, however, the yllable, just preceding the accent- d ( उदात्त ) syllable, was uttered ith a very low tone, it was call- d अनुदात्ततर, while if the syllables ucceeding the accented syllable howed a gradual fall in case they appened to be consecutive and ore than two, the syllable suc- eeding the उदात्त was given a id-way tone, called स्वरितः cf.



 दात्तादनुदात्तस्य स्वरितः, Thus, in the tterance of Vedic hymns the ractice of three tones उदात्त, अनुदात्त nd स्वरित came in vogue and ccordingly they are found defined n all the Prātiśākhya and grammar orks;cf. उच्चैरुदात्तः,नीचैरनुदात्तः समाहारः ्वरितः P.I.2.29-31, T.Pr.I.38-40, .Pr.I.108-110, Anudātta is efined by the author of the Kāśi- āvṛtti as यस्मिन्नुच्चार्यमाणे गात्राणामन्ववसर्गो ाम शिथिलीभवनं भवति, स्वरस्य मृदुता, कण्ट- िवरस्य उरुता च स: अनुदात्तः cf. अन्ववसर्गो ार्दवमुरुता स्वस्येति नीचैःकराणि शब्दस्य . Bh. on I.2.29,30. Cf. also दात्तश्चानुदात्तश्च स्वरितश्च त्रयः स्वराः | अायाम- िश्रम्भोक्षपैस्त उच्यन्तेSक्षराश्रयाः | R. Pr. II.1. The term anudātta is trans- ated by the word 'grave as oppo- ed to acute' (udātta,) and 'circu- flex' (svarita); (2) a term appli- d to such roots as have their owel अनुदात्त or grave, the chief haracteristic of such roots being he non-admission of the augment  before an ārdhadhātuka affix laced after them. ( See अनिट्, ).

'''अनुदात्ततर''' quite a low tone, comple- ely grave; generally applied to he tone of that grave or anudātta owel which is immediately follow- d by an acute ( उदात्त ) vowel. hen the three Vedic accents ere sub-divided into seven tones iz. उदात्त, उदात्ततर्, अनुदात्त, अनुदात्ततर, ्वरित, स्वरितस्थोदात्त and एकश्रुति corres- onding to the seven musical notes, he अनुदात्ततर was the name given o the lowest of them all. अनुदात्ततर as termed सन्नतर also; cf. उदात्तस्वरित- रस्य सन्नतरः P.I.2.40; cf. also M, Bh. n I.2.33.

'''अनुदात्ता''' a term meaning 'having a rave accent,' used by ancient rammarians.Cf. किमियमेकश्रुतिरुदात्ता त अनुदात्ता M. Bh.on I. 2.33.



'''अनुदात्तेत्''' lit. one whose mute signifi- atory letter is uttered with a grave ccent: a term applied to a root haracterized by an indicatory ute vowel accented grave, the hief feature of such a root being hat it takes only the Ātmanepada ffixes c. g. आस्ते, वस्ते, etc.; cf. नुदात्तङित आत्मनेपदम् P. I.3.12; such  root, in forming a derivative ord in the sense of habit, takes he affix युच् e. g. वर्त्तनः, वर्धन: etc. rovided the root begins with a onsonant; cf. अनुदात्तेतश्र हलादेः P. II.2.149.

'''अनुदात्तोपदेश''' (a root) pronounced ori- inally i. c. pronounced in the hātupāṭha with a grave accent; ee the word अनुदात्त above: cf. नुदात्तोपदेशवनतितनोत्यादीनाभनुनासिकलोपो लि ङ्किति P. VI.4.37. See also the ord अनिट् above.

'''अनुदेश''' (1) reference, mention, state- ent referring to a preceding ele- ent. cf. यथासंख्यमनुदेशः समानाम् P.I. .10; cf. आसिद्धवचनात् सिद्धमिति चेद् उत्सर्ग- क्षणनामनुदेशः M. Bh. I.1.57, Vārt. 3. 2) declaration, prescription : the ame as अतिदेश. cf. स्थान्यादेशपृथक्त्वादेशे ्थानिवद् अनुदेशो गुरुवद् गुरुपुत्र इति यथा P. .1.56 Vārt. 1; (3) a grammatical peration cf. यथासंख्यमनुदेशः समानाम् ! मसंबन्धी विधिर्यथासंख्यं स्यात् Sid. Kau. n P.I. 8.10. See the word अनुद्देश n this sense cf. संख्यातानामनूद्देशो यथा- ंख्यम् V, Pr.I.143.

'''अनुनाद''' a fore-sound : a preceding dditional sound which is looked pon as a fault: e. g. ह्वयामि hom pronounced as अह्वयामि. This ound is uttered before an initial onant consonant. It is also utter- d before initial aspirates or visarga. f. घोषवतामनुनादः पुरस्ताद् आदिस्थानां, क्रियते ारणं वा । सोष्मोष्माणामनुनादोप्यनादः R. Pr. IV.18,19.




'''अनुनासिक''' (a letter) uttered through he nose and mouth both, as differ- nt from anusvāra which is uttered nly through the nose. cf. मुखनासिका- चनोनुनासिकःP.I.1.8, and M. Bh. hereon. The anunāsika or nasal etters are the fifth letters of the five lasses ( i.e. ङ् ञ्, ण्, न् , म् ) as also owels अ, इ, उ and semivowels hen so pronounced, as ordinarily hey are uttered through the outh only: ( e.g. अँ, आँ, etc. r य्यँ, व्वँ, ल्लँ etc. in सय्यँन्ता, सव्वँत्सरः, ँल्लीनः etc.) The अनुनासिक or asalized vowels are named रङ्गवर्ण nd they are said to be con- isting of three mātras. cf. अष्टौ द्यानवसानेsप्रगृह्यान् आचार्या आहुरनुना- िकान् स्वरान् | तात्रिमात्रे शाकला दर्शयन्ति . Pr. I.63.64; cf. also अप्रग्रहाः मानाक्षराणि अनुनासिकानि एकेषाम् T. Pr V.6. Trivikrama, a commentator n the Kāt. Sūtras, explains अनुनासिक s अनु पश्चात् नासिकास्थानं उच्चारणं एषां त्यनुनासिकाः| पूर्वं मुखस्थानमुच्चारणं पश्चा- ्नासिकास्थानमुच्चारणमित्यर्थः | अनुग्रहृणात्केवल- ासिकास्थानोच्चारणस्य अनुस्वारस्य नेयं संज्ञा । nd remarks further पूर्वाचार्यप्रसिद्धसंज्ञे- मन्वर्था । Com. by Tr. on Kat. I .13. Vowels which are uttered asalized by Pāṇini in his works iz. सूत्रपाठ, धातुपाठ, गणपाठ etc. are ilent ones i. e. they are not actu- lly found in use. They are put by im only for the sake of a com- lete utterance, their nasalized ature being made out only by eans of traditional convention. . g. एध, स्पर्ध etc. cf. उपदेशेSजनुनासिक त् P.I.3.2; cf. also प्रतिज्ञानुनासिक्याः ाणिनीयाः Kāś on I.3.2.

'''अनुन्यास''' a commentary on न्यास (काशि- ाविवरणपञ्जिका by जिनेन्द्रबुद्धि). The work s believed to have been written by न्दुमित्र. It is not available at pre-


 ent except in the form of refer- nces to it which are numerous specially in Siradeva's Paribhā- āvṛtti.

'''अनुपपत्ति''' discord, absence of validity, ncorrect interpretation; cf.प्रथमानुपप- ्तिस्तु M.Bh on I.4.9. नुपपद्यमाना impossibility of being xplained; cf. तत्र सिद्धायां अनुपपद्यमा- ायां इतरथा उपपादयिषेत्, Nir II.2.

'''अनुपपन्न''' impossible to be explained, ot consistent , cf. अथाप्यनुपपन्नार्था वन्ति | ओषधे त्रायस्वैनम् | Nir. I.15. नुपरिपाद्य (संहिता) the Pada text of he Vedic Saṁhitā.

'''अनुपसर्जन''' not subordinated in word- elation, principal member; cf. अनु- सर्जनात् P. IV.I.14 and M.Bh. hereon; cf also Par. Śek Pari. 26.

'''अनुप्रदान''' an effort outside the mouth n the production of sound at he different vocal organs such s कण्ठ, तालु etc. which is looked pon as an external effort or āhyaprayatna. अनुप्रदान is one of the hree main factors in the produc- ion of sound which are ( 1 ) स्थान,  2 ) करण or आभ्यन्तरप्रयत्न and ( 3 ) नुप्रदान or बाह्यप्रयत्न; cf. स्थाकरणप्रयत्नेभ्यो र्णा जायन्ते Cān. The commentator n T. Pr. describes अनुप्रदान as the ूलकारण or उपादानकारण, the main ause in the production of articu- ate sound cf. अनुप्रदीयते अनेन वर्णः इति नुप्रदानम्: cf also अनुप्रदीयते इत्यनुप्रदानं ्रयत्न इत्यर्थः; Uvvaṭa on R. Pr. XIII. . Generally two main varieties f बाह्यप्रयत्न are termed अनुप्रदान which re mentioned as (i) श्वासानुप्रदान emission of breath) and नादानुप्रदान resonance), the other varieties of t such as विवार, संवार, घोष, अघोष, ल्पप्राण, मह्मप्राण, उदात्त, अनुदात्त and ्वरित being called merely as ाह्यप्रयत्न.




'''अनुप्रयोग''' subsequent utterance; lit. ost-position as in the case of the oots कृ, भू and अम् in the periphra- tic perfect forms; cf. आम्प्रत्ययवत् कृञोऽ ुप्रयोगस्य, P.I.3.63; यथाविध्यनुप्रयोगः ूर्वस्मिन् III.4.4.

'''अनुबन्ध''' a letter or letters added to a ord before or after it, only to ignify some specific purpose such s (a) the addition of an afix e. g. क्त्रि, अथुच् अङ् etc.) or (b) the ubstitution of गुण, वृद्धि or संप्रसारण owel or (c) sometimes their preven- ion. These anubandha letters are ermed इत् (lit. going or disappear- ng) by Pāṇini (cf. उपदेशेजनुनासिक त् etc. I.3.2 to 9), and they do ot form an essential part of the ord to which they are attached, he word in usage being always ound without the इत् letter. For echnical purposes in grammar, owever, such as आदित्व or अन्तत्व of ffixes which are characterized y इत् letters, they are looked pon as essential factors, cf. नेकान्ता अनुबन्धाः, एकान्ता:, etc, Par. ek. Pari. 4 to 8. Although पाणिनि as invariably used the term इत् or अनुबन्ध letters in his Sūtras, atañjali and other reputed writers n Pāṇini's grammar right on upto āgeśa of the 18th century have sed the term अनुबन्ध of ancient rammarians in their writings in he place of इत्. The term अनुबन्ध as chosen for mute significatory etters by ancient grammarians robably on account of the ana- ogy of the अनुबन्ध्य पशु, tied down t sacrifices to the post and ubsequently slaughtered.

'''अनुभूतिस्वरूपाचार्य''' a writer of the welfth century who wrote a work n grammar called सरस्वती-प्रक्रिया r सारस्वतप्रक्रिया, He has also written


 ातुपाठ and आख्यातप्रक्रिया. The gram- ar is a short one and is studied n some parts of India.

'''अनुम्''' not allowing the addition of the ugment नुम् (i.e. letter न् ) after he last vowel; The term is used, n connection with the present part. ffix, by Pāṇini in his rule शतुरनुमो द्यजादी VI.1.173.

'''अनुमान''' inference,suggestion, cf. शक्या क्रिया पिण्डीभूता निदर्शयितुम् ।  ासामनुमानगम्या M. Bh. on I.3.1.

'''अनुलोम''' in the natural order (opp. o प्रतिलोम ), cf. तेऽन्वक्षरसंधयोनुलोमाः in .Pr.II.8. अनुलोमसंधि is a term pplied to Saṁdhis with a vowel irst and a consonant afterwards.

'''अनुलोमसंधि''' combination according o the alphabetical order; a kind of uphonic alteration ( संधि ) where he vowel comes first. e.g- हव्यवाट् + ग्निः where ट् is changed to द्; एषः ेवः= एष देवः cf. R. Pr. II. 8. (Sce नुलोम ).

'''अनुवर्तन''' continuation or recurrence f a word from the preceding to he succeeding rule; the same as nuvṛtti; cf. अनुवर्तन्ते नाम विधयः । न ानुवर्तनादेव भवन्ति। किं तर्हि । यत्नाद्भवन्तीति . Bh. on I.1.3.

'''अनुवर्त्य''' to be observed, to be obeyed; f. न लक्षणेन पदकाराः अनुवर्त्याः । पदकारैर्नाम क्षणमनुवर्त्यम् M.Bh. on  III.1.109.

'''अनुवाद''' repetition of a rule already aid down or of a statement already ade cf. प्रमाणान्तरावगतस्य अर्थस्य शब्देन ंकीर्तनमात्रमनुवाद: Kāś. on II.4.3.

'''अनुविधि''' operation in conformity with hat is found. The expression न्दसि दृष्टानुविधिः is often found in the ahābhāṣya: cf. M. Bh. on I.1.5, .1.6, I.1.21, III.1.9, III.1.13, I.1.6, VI.1.77, VI.1.79, VI. .128,VI.4.141, VIII.2.108.




'''अनुवृत्ति''' repetition or recurrence of a ord from the previous to the sub- equent rule or rules, which is ecessary for the sake of the intend- d interpretation. The word is of ommon use in books on Pāṇini's rammar. This recurrence is gene- ally continuous like the stream of  river ( गङ्गास्रोतोवत् ); sometimes owever, when it is not required in  n intermediate rule, although it  roceeds further, it is named ण्डूकप्लुत्यानुवृत्ति. In rare cases it is aken backwards in a sūtra work rom a subsequent rule to a pre- ious rule when it is called अपकर्ष.

