'''अागन्तुक''' lit. adventitious, an addi- ional wording generally at the nd of roots to show distinctly heir form e.g. वदि, एधि, सर्ति etc.; f. इन्धिभवतिभ्यां च P I.2.6: cf. lso भावलक्षणे स्थेकृञ्वदिचरिहृतभिजनि- ्यस्तोमुन्, P.III.4.16, सृपवृदो. कसुन् P. II.4.17 and a number of other ūtras where इ or तिं is added to he root cf. इक्श्तिपौ धातुनिर्देशे, वर्णा- ्कारः, रादिफः P.III.3.108 Vārt. 2.3. , where such appendages to be dded to the roots or letters are iven. The word अागन्तु is an old ord used in the Nirukta, but the erm आगन्तुक appears to be used or the first time for such forms y Haradatta; cf. ह्वरोरिति ह्वृ कौटिल्ये, गन्तुकेकारे गुणेन निर्देशः Padamañjarī on II.2.31. In the traditional oral xplanations the second part of a eduplicated word is termed ागन्तुक which is placed second


 . e. after the original by vir- ue of the convention आगन्तू- ामन्ते निवेशः, although in fact, it s said to possess the sense of he root in contrast with the irst which is called abhyāsa.A nice istinction can, however be drawn etween the four kinds of adventi- ious wordings found in grammar iz.आगन्तु, इत्, अभ्यास and आगम which an be briefly stated as follows; he former two do not form a egular part of the word and are ot found in the actual use of the ord; besides, they do not possess ny sense, while the latter two are ound in actual use and they are ossessed of sense. Again the gantu word is simply used for acility of understanding exactly  nd correctly the previous word  hich is really wanted; the इत्  ording, besides serving this pur- ose, is of use in causing some rammatical operations. अभ्यास, is he first part of the wording which s wholly repeated and it possesses o sense by itself, while, āgama hich is added to the word either t the beginning or at the end or nserted in the middle, forms a art of the word and possesses the ense of the word.

'''आगम''' augment, accrement, a word lement which is added to the rimitive or basic word during the rocess of the formation of a com- lete word or pada. The āgama s an adventitious word element nd hence differs from ādeśa, the ubstitute which wholly takes the lace of the original or ( आदेशिन् ). ut of the several āgamas men- ioned by Pāṇini, those that are arked with mute ट् are prefixed, hose, marked with क्, are affixed, hile those, marked with म्, are
 laced immediately after the last owel of the word. The aug- ents become a part and parcel f the word to which they are dded, and the characteristics of hich they possess;cf.यदागमास्तद्गुणी- ूतास्तद्ग्रहणेन गृह्यन्ते, also आगमानां आगमि- र्मिवैशिष्ट्यम् Par. Śek. Pari.11. Those rammarians, who hold the wiew hat words are unproduced and ternal, explain the addition of an ugment as only the substitution f a word with an augment in the lace of a word without an aug- ent; cf. आदेशास्तर्हिमे भविष्यन्ति अनाग- कानां सागमकाः M. Bh. on I.1.20; .1.46. The term āgama is defined s अन्यत्र विद्यमानस्तु यो वर्णः श्रुयतेधिकः । गम्यमानतुल्यत्वात्स आगम इति स्मृतः Com. n Tait. Prāt.I. 23.

