'''अाङ्''' the preposition आ. See the ord आ above. 

'''अाङ्ग''' an operation prescribed in the ection, called aṅgādhikāra, in the he Aṣṭādhyāyī of Pāṇini, made up f five Pādas consisting of the ourth quarter of the 6th adhyāya nd all the four quarters of the eventh adhyāya. आङ्गात् पूर्वं विकरणा षितव्याः M. Bh on I.3.60 Vārt.


 ; cf, also वार्णादाङ्गं बलीयो भवति Par. ek. Pari 55: also M. Bh. on II.2.3.

'''आच्''' tad. affix आ applied to the ord दक्षिणा and उत्तरा; cf.P.V. 3.36, 8. e. g. दक्षिणा वसति, उत्तरा रमणीयम् āś on V.3.36, 38.

'''आचार''' (1) customary usage of putting r employing words in rules; cf. चार्यचारात्संज्ञासिद्धिः, P.I,1.1, Vārt. 4. 2) behaviour;cf. उपमानादाचारे P.III. .10; cf also निवासत आचारतश्च M.Bh. n VI.3.109.

'''आचारक्विप्''' denom. affix क्विप् applied o any prātipadika or noun in the ense of behaviour: cf. सर्वप्रातिपदिकेभ्य चारे क्विब् वक्तव्यः अश्वति गर्दभति इत्येवमर्थम् . Bh. on III.1.11; cf. हलन्तेभ्य चाराक्विबभावाच्च Par. Śek. on Pari.52.

'''आचार्य''' preceptor, teacher; a designa- ion usually given to Pāṇini by atañjali in the Mahābhāṣya; cf. he usual expression तज्ज्ञापयति आचार्यः s also अाचार्यप्रवृत्तिर्ज्ञापयति; also cf. ेदानीमाचार्याः सूत्राणि कृत्वा निवर्तयन्ति; cf. lso the popular definition of ाचार्य given as 'निशम्य यद्गिरं प्राज्ञा विचार्यैव तत्क्षणम् । संभावयन्ति शिरसा माचार्यं प्रचक्षते ।"

'''आचार्यदेशीय''' a partisan of the precep- or Pāṇini or the Sūtrakāra who is ooked upon as having approx- ately the same authority as the ūtrakāra; cf. अाचार्यदेशीय अाह- न क्तव्य इति l Kaiyaṭa on I.4.105, ārt. 2.

'''आचार्यसंपद्''' necessary qualification to each the Veda with all its pāṭhas aving the necessary knowledge f accents, matrās and the like. cf. दक्रमविभागज्ञो वर्णक्रमविचक्षणः स्वरमात्राविशे- ज्ञो गच्छेदाचार्यसंपदम् R. Prāt.I.8.

'''आचितादि''' a class of words headed by he word अाचित which do not have heir final vowel accented acute
 y P. VI.2.146 when they are receded by the prepositions प्र, परा tc. although they are used as roper nouns. e.g. आचितम्नि,निरुक्तम, ्रश्लिष्टम्; cf. Kāśikā on P. VI.2.146.

'''अाट्''' (1) augment अा prefixed to roots eginning with a vowel in the mperfect, aorist and conditional, hich is always accented (उदात्त); f. P.VI.4.72; (2) augment अा refixed to the imperative first erson terminations, e.g. करवाणि, रवै etc.; cf. P.III.4.92: (3) aug- ent अा to be prefixed to case- ffixes which are डित् after nouns alled nadī: e.g. कुमार्यं; cf P.VII. .112.

'''अाटच्''' tad.affix (आट) in the sense of ossession added to the word वाच्; .g. वाचाटः cf. P.V.2.125.

'''अात्''' (1) long अा as different from short r protracted अ prescribed by the ofd वृद्धि or दीर्घ in the case of अ, r by the word अात् when substitu- ed for another vowel, as for exam- le in the rule आदेच उपदेशेऽशिति and he following: cf. P.VI.1.45, 57; 2) substitute for the ablative affix स् after words ending in अ; cf. P. I.1.12; (3) substitute अात् for a ase affix in Vedic Literature, e.g.  ताद् ब्राह्मणाद् निन्दामि Kāś. on VII. .39.

'''आताम्''' Ātmanepada third person dual nding, technically substituted for कार by P.III.4.78

'''अाति''' tad. affix अात् applied to उत्तर, धर and दक्षिण by P.V.3.34.

'''आतिदेशिक''' applied by extension or ransfer of epithet as opposed to पदेशिक. See the word अतिदेश; the erm is often used in connection ith rules or operations which do ot apply or occur by the direct xpression of the grammarian; cf. दि आतिदेशिकेन कित्वेन औपदेशिकं कित्वं


 ाध्येत. M. Bh. on I.2.1.; cf. also ातिदेशिकमनित्यम् Par.Śek. Pari. 93.6.

'''आतिशायिक''' a tad-affix in the sense f excellence; a term applied to he affixes तम and इष्ठ as also तर and यस् prescribed by Pāṇini by the ules अतिशायने तमबिष्ठनौ and द्विवचन- िभज्योपपदे तरबीयसुनौ cf. P.V.3.55, 57. his superlative affix is seen doub- y applied sometimes in Vedic Lit. g.श्रेष्ठतमाय कर्मणे Yaj. Saṁ. I.1; cf. lso तदन्ताच्च स्वार्थे छन्दसि दर्शनं श्रेष्ठतमायेति .V.3.55 Vārt.3.

'''आतिशायिकान्त''' a word ending with an tisāyika affix; cf. अातिदायिकान्तात्स्वार्थे न्दसि आतिशायिको दृश्यते M. Bh. on V. .55.

'''आत्त्व''' the substitution of long अा rescribed by the term अात् as in देच उपदेशेऽस्ति and the following f. P. VI.1.45 etc.

'''आत्मन्''' agent or Kaṛtr as in the terms ात्मनेपद or अात्मनेभाषा, cf. सुप आत्मनः ्यच् III. 1.8.

'''आत्मनेपद्''' a technical term for the ffixes called तड् (त, आताम् etc.) and he affix अान ( शानच् , चानच् कानच् ), alled so possibly because, the ruit of the activity is such as enerally goes to the agent (आत्मने) hen these affixes are used. Con- rast this term (Ātmanepada) ith the term Parasmaipada when he fruit is meant for another. For n explanation of the terms see P. I.3.7 and 8.

'''अात्मनेपदिन्''' a root which always takes he Ātmanepada affixes. (See bove).

'''अात्मनेभाष''' a technical term used for uch roots as speak for the agent imself; the term अात्मनेभाष means he same as the term अात्मनेपदिन्. he term अात्मनेभाष is not mention- d by Pāṇini; but the writer of the ārtikas explains it, cf. आत्मने-
 ाषपरस्मैभाषयोरुपसंख्यानम् P. VI.3.7 and  Vārt. 1; cf. also आत्मनेपदिनश्च धातवो ैयाकरणैरात्मनभाषशब्देन व्यवह्रियन्ते,Kaiyaṭa n VI.3.7.The term is found in the tharva-Prātiśākhya. III. 4.7. It annot be said whether the term amein use after Pāṇini or, although arlier, it belonged to some school ther than that of Pāṇini or, Pāṇini ut into use the terms Ātmane- ada and Parasmaipada for the ffixes as the ancient terms Ātman- bhāṣa and Parasmaibhāṣa were in se for the roots.

'''अात्व''' the substitution of अा; e.g. तादृक्, वादृक्, अन्यादृक् cf. आ सर्वनाम्नः P.VI.3. 0.

'''आत्वत्''' possessed of the vowel आ; ontaining the vowel आ; e.g पाकः, ायः etc. cf. कर्षात्वतो घञोन्त उदात्तः P.VI. .159.

'''आदादिक''' belonging to the second con- ugation or class of roots which egins with the root अद्; cf. दैवादि- स्यैव ग्रहणं भविष्यति नादादिकस्य Pur.Pari. 7.

'''अादि''' (1) commencement, initial: cf. पूर्वलक्षण आदिः M.Bh. on I.1.21, (2) f the kind of, similar; एवंप्रक्रारः.

'''आदिकर्मन्''' commencement of an action; f. आदिभूतः क्रियाक्षणः अदिकर्म Kāś. on दिकर्मणि क्तः कर्तरि च । P.III.4.71.

'''आदित्''' possessed of the mute indica- ory letter अा signifying the non- pplication of the augment इ (इट् ) o the past-pass. part. term क्त. e. . क्ष्विण्ण from the root ञ्क्ष्विदाः simi- arly खिन्न, भिन्न etc. cf. आदितश्र P.VII. .16.

'''आदिवृद्धि''' the Vṛddhi substitute pres- ribed for the first vowel of a word o which a tad-affix, marked with he mute letter ञ्,ण्, or क् is added; .g. औपगव, दाक्षि etc.; cf. तद्धितेष्वचामादेः .VII.2.117, 118.


 दिष्ट (1) prescribed for substitution; pecified for an operation : cf. सिद्धे ु आदिष्टस्य युड्वचनात् M.Bh. on VI.1. 55; cf. also M. Bh. on VI. 1.I58 ārt. 3; M. Bh. on IV.3.28 Vār. ; cf. also आदिष्टानैवाचः पूर्वः M. Bh. n I.1.57; (2) indicated or stated; ादिष्टा इमे वर्णाः.

'''आदेश''' (1) substitute as opposed to thānin, the original. In Pāṇini's rammar there is a very general axim, possessed of a number of xceptions, no doubt, that 'the ubstitute behaves like the origi- al' (स्थानिवदादेशः अनल्विधौ P.I.1.56.); he application of this maxim is alled स्थानिवद्भाव; for purposes of his स्थानिवद्भाव the elision (लोप) of a honetic element is looked upon s a sort of substitute;cf. उपधालेपस्य ्थानिवत्त्वात् Kāś. on P.I.1.58. Gram- arians many times look upon a omplete word or a word-base as  substitute for another one, alth- ugh only a letter or a syllable in he word is changed into another, s also when a letter or syllable is dded to or dropped in a word; f. पचतु, पचन्तु ... इमेप्यादेशाः । कथम् । ादिश्यते यः स आदेशः । इमे चाप्यादिश्यन्ते . Bh. on I.1.56; cf also सर्वे सर्व- दादेशा दाक्षीपुत्रस्य पाणिनेः M.Bh. on P. .1.20; cf. also अनागमकानां सागमका देशाः M. Bh. on I.1.20: (2) indi- ation, assignment; cf. योयं स्वरादेशः न्तोदात्तं, वधेराद्युदात्तत्वं, स्वः स्वरितमिति ादेशः R.Pr.I.30-32; cf. also अादेशः पदेशः com. on Tai.-Prāt. II.20: f. also अनादेशे अविकारः V.Pr.IV.131, here Uvvaṭa remarks यत्र उदात्तादीनां ्वराणां सन्धौ आदेशो न क्रियते तत्र अविकारः ्रत्येतव्यः । cf. also एकारो विभक्त्यादेशः न्दसि A.Pr. II.1.2, where ए is pres- ribed as a substitute for a case- ffix and त्वे and अत्वे are cited as xamples where the acute acent is lso prescribed for the substitute ए.

'''आदेशिन्''' that for which a substitute s prescribed; the original, sthā- in: cf. आदेशिानामादेशाः cf. also M. h. On P.I.1.56.

'''आद्य''' (1) premier; cf. इदमाद्यं पदस्थानं व्याकरणनामकं ) सिद्धिसोपानपर्वणाम् Vāk. ad. I.16; (2) preceding as oppo- ed to succeeding (उत्तर); cf. सहाद्यौ- ्व्यञ्जनैः V.Pr.I.100 (3) original; cf. द्यप्रकृतिः परमप्रकृतिः (original base) hāṣā Vṛtti. IV.1.93; (4) first, receding, आद्ये योगे न व्यवाये तिङः स्यु; .Bh. on III.1-91.

'''आद्यन्तवत्त्व''' अाद्यन्तवद्भाव, consideration f a single or solitary letter as the nitial or the final one according o requirements for opcrations rescribed for the initial or for he final. Both these notions --the nitial and the final-are relative otions, and because they require he presence of an additional letter r letters for the sake of being alled initial or final it becomes ecessary to prescribe आद्यन्तवद्भाव in he case of a single letter; cf.अाद्यन्त- देकस्मिन् । आदौ इव अन्त इव एकस्मिन्नपि ार्यं भवति । यथा कर्तव्यमित्यत्र प्रत्ययाद्युदात्तत्वं वति एवमौपगवमित्यत्रापि यथा स्यात् । Kāś. n P.I.1.21 ; cf. also अाद्यन्तवच्च । पृक्तस्य आदेवदन्तवच्च कार्यं भवति । T. Pr. .55. This अाद्यन्तवद्भाव of Pāṇini is, n fact, a specific application of he general maxim known as yapadeśivadbhāva by virtue of hich "an operation which affects omething on account of some pecial designation, which for ertain reasons attaches to the etter, affects likewise that which tands alone;" cf. Pari.Śek. Pari. 0.

'''आद्युदात्त''' a word beginning with an cute-accent i.e. which has got the irst vowel accented acute: words n the vocative case and words


 ormed with an affix marked with  mute ञ् or न् are ādyudātta; cf.P. I.1.197, 198: for illustrations in etail see P.VI.1.189-216.

'''आद्युदात्तनिपातन''' specific mention of a ord with the accent udātta or cute on the first syllable; cf. द्युदात्तनिपातनं करिष्यते M.Bh. on I.1. 6, VI.1.12.

'''आधार''' receptacle or abode of an ction;cf.अाश्रियन्ते अस्मिन्ख्म क्रियाः इत्याधारः āś. on P.I.4.45 also M. Bh. on II.3.121; the Prakriyā Kaumudī entions four kinds of ādhāras: cf. पश्लेषिकः सामीपिको विषयो व्याप्त इत्याघारश्च- ुर्धा Prak. Kau. on II.3.36.

'''अाधाराधेयभाव''' a non-differential rela- ion (अभेदसंसर्ग) between the perso- al endings तिप् , तस् etc. and the oun in the nominative case hich is the subject of the verbal ctivity;relation of a thing and its ubstratum: cf. निपातातिरिक्तनामार्थ- ात्वर्थयोर्भेदान्वयस्य अव्युत्पन्नत्वात्.

'''आधिक्य''' superfluity, superiority, otion of surplus; cf यदत्राधिक्यं ाक्यार्थः सः M. Bh. on II.3.46, II.3. 0.

'''आधृषीय''' a sub-division of roots belon- ing to the चुरादिगण or tenth conju- ation beginning with युज् and end- ng with धृष् which take the Vika- aṇa णिच् optionally i.e. which are lso conjugated like roots of the irst conjugation; e.g. यीजयति,योजयते, ोजति;साहयति-ते, सहति.

'''आधेय''' a thing placed in another or epending upon another, as oppo- ed to ādhāra or the container; cf. धेयश्चाक्रियाजश्च सोसत्त्वप्रकृतिर्गुणः M. Bh. n P.IV.1.44.

'''आन''' (1) kṛt affix (शानच् or चानश्) substi-tuted for the lakāra लट् and appli- d to ātmanepadi roots forming he present participle; (2) kṛt. affix ानच् applied to ātmanepadi roots
 n the sense of past time forming he perfect participle cf. लिटः ानज्वा P.III.2.106.

'''अानङ्''' substitute आन्in the place ofthe ast letter (ऋ) of the first member f dvandva compounds of words eaning deities or of words show- ng blood-relationship which end ith the vowel ऋ; e.g. होतापोतारौ, ातापितरो cf. P.VI.3.25, 26.

'''अनन्तर्य''' (1) close proximity; absence f any intermediary element enerally of the same nature: नन्तरस्य भावः आनन्तर्यम् cf. नाजानन्तर्ये हृिष्ट्वप्रक्लतिः M. Bh. I.4.2. Vārt. 21: ar. Śek. Pari. 51. This close proxi- ity of one letter or syllable or so, ith another, is actually i.e.phone- ically required and generally so ound out also, but sometimes such roximity is theoretically not xisting as the letter required or proximity is technically not resent there by the rule पूर्वत्रासिद्धम्. n such cases, a technical absence s not looked upon as a fault. cf. चिच्च संनिपातकृतमानन्तर्ये शास्त्रकृतमनानन्तर्ये था ष्टुत्वे, क्वचिच्च नैव संनिपातकृतं नापि ास्त्रकृतं यथा जश्त्वे । यत्र कुतश्चिदेवानन्तर्यं र्वाद्यानन्तर्यं M. Bh. on VIII.3.13. 2) close connection by mention ogether at a common place etc.;cf. र्वाद्यानन्तर्यं कार्यार्थम् M. Bh. on I.1.27.

'''अानन्ददत्त''' name of a Buddhist rammarian,the author of the ork named Cāndra-vyākaraṇa addhati.

'''आनर्थक्य''' absence of any utility; uperfluity; absence of any object r purpose; cf. स्थानिवद्वचनानर्थक्यं शास्त्रा- िद्धत्वात् । M. Bh. on P.VI.1.86 ārt. 5 cf. also P.VI.1.158 Vārt. ; VI.1.161 Vārt. 1, VI.1.166 ārt. 1, VI.1.167 Vārt. 3. ानि imp. 1st per.sing affix नि with he augment अा prefixed, which


 as got its न् changed into ण् by P. III.4.16.

'''आनुक्''' the augment आन्, added to the ords इन्द्र, वरुण, भव and others efore the fem. affix ई; e.g. इन्द्राणी, रुणानी cf. इन्द्रवरुणभवशर्वरुद्र...आनुक् P. V.1.49.

'''आनुनासिक्य''' nasalization; utterance hrough the nose, an additional roperty possessed by vowels and he fifth letters of the 5 classes (ङ्, ्, ण् ,न्, म्) cf. आनुनासिक्यं तेषामधिको ुणः M.Bh. on I.1.9.

'''आनुपूर्वी''' serial order, successive order f grammatical operations or the ules prescribing them as they ccur; cf. अानुपूर्व्या सिद्धमेतत् M.Bh. on .3.5; cf. also ययैव चानुपूर्व्या अर्थानां ्रादुर्भावस्तयैव शब्दानामपि । तद्वत् कार्यैरपि वितव्यम् M.Bh. on. P.I.1.57.

'''आनुपूर्व्य''' successive order, as prescri- ed by tradition or by the writer; f. ऋतुनक्षत्राणामानुपूर्व्येण समानाक्षराणां पूर्वनि- ातः । शिशिरवसन्तौ उदगयनस्थौ । कृत्तिका- ोहिण्यः । M.Bh. II.2.34 Vārt.3;also र्णानामानुपूर्व्येण ब्राह्मणक्षत्रियविट्शूद्राः M.Bh. n II.2.34 Vārt. 6: cf. पदानुपूर्व्येण ्रश्लिष्टान् संधीन् कुर्यात् । इन्द्र अा इहि । आदौ न्द्र आ इत्येतयोः; न तु अा इहि इत्येतयाः . Pr. II.2; cf. also आनुपूर्व्यात् सिद्धम् īra. Pari. 6.

'''आनुपूर्व्यसंहिता''' the saṁhitā-pāṭha or ecital of the running Vedic text n accordance with the constituent ords;e.g. शुनः शेपं चित् निदितम् or रा शंसं वा पूषणम्, as opposed to the नानुपूर्व्यसंहिता which is actually found n the traditional recital e.g. ुनश्चिच्छेपं निदितम् Ṛk saṁh. V 2.7 or रा वा शंसं पूषणम् Ṛk saṁh. X.64.3. ee R. Prāt. II 43.

'''आनुमानिक''' obtained or made out by nference such,as Paribhāṣā rules s opposed to Śrauta rules such as he Sūtras of Pāṇini; cf. आनुमानिकं ्थानित्वमवयवयो; Kāś. on VI.1.85;
 lso cf. आनुमानिकस्थान्यादेशभावकल्पनेपि ्रौतस्थान्यादेशभावस्य न त्यागः Par. Śek. n Pari. 11; cf. also किं च पूर्वत्रेत्यस्य ्रत्यक्षत्वेन अानुमानिक्या अस्या बाध एवोचितः ari. Śek. on Pari. 50.

'''अान्तरतम्य''' closest affinity; cf. अष्टन्- नादिपथिमथ्यात्वेषु आन्तरतम्यादनुनासिकप्रसङ्गः .Bh. on VII.2.84, as also अान्तर- म्याच्च सिद्धम् M. Bh. on VII.1. 96 ārt. 6.

'''अान्तर्य''' proximity; close affinity ; close elationship. There are four kinds fsuch proximity as far as words n grammar are concerned; Re: the rgans of speech (स्थानतः)as in दण्डा- ्रम्, regarding the meaning(अर्थत:)as n वातण्ड्ययुवतिः, regarding the quality गुण) as in पाकः रागः, and regarding he prosodial value (प्रमाण) as is मुष्मै, अमूभ्याम् cf. अनेकविधे अान्तर्य ्थानार्थगुणप्रमेाणकृतम् Par. Śek. Pari.13. f. also Kāś. on I.1.50.

'''अान्पद्''' word ending with अान् which as the consonant dropped and he preceding आ nasalized; e. g. र्गाँ इव सृजतम् Ṛk.Saṁh. VIII. 35. 20, ई इन्द्रः Ṛk Saṁh VI.19.1; cf. दीर्घादटि मानपादे, अातेऽटि नित्यम् P. VIII.3.9, III.3.3; cf. also हन्त देवो इति चैता ान्-पदाः पदवृत्तयः R.Pr.IV.26,27.

