'''इत्''' (1) a letter or a group of letters ttached to a word which is not
 een in actual use in the spoken anguage: cf अप्रयोगी इत्, Śāk. I.1.5, em.1.1.37. The इत् letters are pplied to a word before it, or fter it, and they have got each of hem a purpose in grammar viz. ausing or preventing certain rammatical operations in the ormation of the complete word. āṇini has not given any defini- ion of the word इत् , but he has entioned when and where the owels and consonants attached to ords are to be understood as इत्; cf. उपदेशेजनुनासिक इत् , हलन्त्यम् । etc. . I.3.2 to 8) and stated that hese letters are to be dropped in ctual use, cf.P.I.3.9. It appears hat grammarians before Pāṇini ad also employed such इत् letters, s is clear from some passages in he Mahābhāṣya as also from heir use in other systems of rammar as also in the Uṇādi list f affixes, for purposes similar to hose found served in Pāṇini 's rammar. Almost all vowels and onsonants are used as इत् for ifferent purposes and the इत् letters re applied to roots in the Dhā- upāṭha, nouns in the Gaṇapāṭha, s also to affixes, augments and ubstitutes prescribed in grammar. nly at a few places they are ttached to give facility of pronun- iation. Sometimes the इत् letters, specially vowels, which are said o be इत्, when uttered as nasalized y Pāṇini, are recognised only by onvention; cf. प्रतिज्ञानुनासिक्याः पाणि- ीयाः(S.K.on P.I.3.2).The word इत्, hich literally means going away r disappearing, can be explained s a mute indicatory letter. In āṇini's grammar, the mute vowel  applied to roots indicates the lacing of the Ātmanepada affixes


 fter them, if it be uttered as anu- ātta and of affixes of both the adas if uttered svarita; cf. P.I.3. 2, 72. The mute vowel आ signi- ies the prevention of इडागम before he past part, affixes; cf. P. VII. . 16. Similarly, the mute vowel इ ignfies the augment न् after the last owel of the root; cf.P.VII.1.58; ई ignifies the prevention of the aug- ent इ before the past part.affixes fP.VII.2.14;उ signifies the inclu- ion of cognate letters; cf.P.I.1.69, nd the optional addition of the ugment इ before त्वा; cf. P.VII.2. 6; ऊ signifies the optional appli- ation of the augment इट्;cf.P.VII. .44; क signifies the prevention of ्रस्व to the vowel of a root before he causal affix, cf.VII.4.2: लृ sig- ifies the vikarana अङ् in the Aorist f P.III.1.55; ए signifies the pre- ention of vrddhi in the Aorist,cf. .VII.2.55; ओ signifies the substi- ution of न् for त् of the past part. f. P VIII.2.45; क् signifies the revention of गुण and वृद्धि, cf.P, I. .5， signifies the addition of the ugment मुम्(म्)and the shortening f the preceding vowel: cf.P.VI.3 5-66: गु signifies the prevention of ुण and वृद्धि, cf. P.I.1.5 घ् signifies ुत्व, cf. P.VII.3.62; ङ्, applied to ffixes, signifies the prevention of ुण and वृद्धि, cf. P.I.1.5; it causes  ंप्रसारणादेश in the case of certain roots, cf. P. VI.1.16 and signifies आत्मनेपद if applied to roots; cf. P.I.3.12, and their substitution for the ast letter if applied to substitutes. f. P I.1.53. च् signifies the acute ccent of the last vowel;cf.P.VI.1. 59; ञ् signifies उभयपद i.e the plac- ng of the affixes of both the podas fter the root to which it has been ffixed;cf.P.I.3.72, ट् in the case of n augment signifies its application
 o the word at the beginning: cf.P .1.64, while applied to a nominal ase or an affix shows the addition f the fem. affix ई (ङीप्) cf.P.IV.1. 5;ड् signifies the elision of the last yllable; cf. P.VI.4.142: ण् signifies ृद्धि, cf.P.VII.2.115;त् signifies स्वरित ccent, cf. VI.1.181, as also that ariety of the vowel ( ह्रस्व, दीर्ध or ्लुत) to which it has been applied f. P.I.1.70; न् signifies आद्युदात्त, cf. .VI.1.193:प् signifies अनुदात्त acccnt f. अनुदात्तौ सुप्पितौ P. III.1.4. as lso उदात्त for the vowel before the ffix marked with पृ cf. P.VI.1.192: ् signifies in the case of an aug- ent its addition after the final owel.cf.P.I.1.47,while in the case f a root, the shortening of its owel before the causal affix णि,cf. .VI.4.92: र् signifies the acute ccent for the penultimate vowel f. P.VI.1.217，signifies the acute ccent for the vowel preceding he affix marked with ल्; cf.P.VI. 93 श् implies in the case of an ffix its सार्वधातुकत्व cf. P. II1.4.113, hile in the case of substitutes, heir substitution for the whole ्थानिन् cf P.I.1.55 प् signifies the ddition of the fem. affix ई ( ङीप् ) f.P.IV-1.41 ;स् in the case of affixes ignifies पदसंज्ञा to the base before hem, cf P.I.4.16. Sometimes even ithout the actual addition of the ute letter, affixes are directed to e looked upon as possessed of that ute letter for the sake ofa gram- atical operation e.g. सार्वधातुकमपित् .I.2.4; असंयेागाल्लिट् कित् P.I.2.5: गोतो ित् P.VII.1.90 etc. (2) thc short owel इ as a substitute: cf. शास दङ्हलोः P.VI.4.34.

