'''उपसर्ग''' preposition, prefix. The ord उसपर्ग originally meant nly  'a prefixed word': cf. सोपसगेषु ामसु R. Pr. XVI. 38. The word ecame technically applied by ncient Sanskrit Gratmmarians to he words प्र, परा, अप, सम् etc. hich are always used along ith a verb or a verbal deriva- ive or a noun showing a verbal ctivity; cf. उपसर्गाः क्रियायोगे P. I. 59. 'These prefixes are necessari- y compounded with the follow- ng word unless the latter is a erbal form; cf. कुगतिप्रादयः P.II. .18. Although they are not ompounded with a verbal form, hese prepositions are used in uxtaposition with it; sometimes hey are found detached from the erbal form even with the inter- ention of one word or more. he prefixes are instrumental in hanging the meaning of the root. ome scholars like Śākaṭāyana old the view that separated from he roots, prefixes do not express ny specific sense as ordinary ords express, while scholars ike Gārgya hold the view that refixes do express a sense e. g. ्र means beginning or प्रारम्भ; cf.  निर्बद्धा उपसर्ग अर्थान्निराहुरिति शाकटायनः | ामाख्यातयोस्तु कर्मोपसंयोगद्योतका भवन्ति | च्चावचाः पदार्था भवन्तीति गार्ग्यः | तद्य एषु दार्थः प्राहुरिमं तं नामाख्यातयोरर्थविकरणम् ir. I. 8. It is doubtful, however, hich view Pāṇini himself held. n his Ātmanepada topic, he has entioned some specific roots 1
 s possessing some specific senses hen preceded by some specific refixes (see P. I.3.20, 24, 25, 0, 4l, 46, 52, 56, etc.), which mplies possibly that roots them- elves possess various senses, while refixes are simply instrumental n indicating or showing them. n the other hand, in the topic f the Karmapravacanīyas,the same ords प्र, परा etc. which, however, re not termed Upasargas for the ime being, although they are alled Nipātas, are actually assign- d some specific senses by Pāṇini. he Vārttikakāra has defined पसर्ग as क्रियाविशेषक उपसर्गः P. I. .I. Vārt 7, leaving it doubtful hether the उपसर्ग or prefix posses- es an independent sense which odifies the sense of the root, r without possessing any inde- endent sense, it shows only the odified sense of the root which lso is possessed by the root. hartṛhari, Kaiyaṭa and their ollowers including Nāgeśa have mphatically given the view that ot only prefixes but Nipātas, hich include प्र, परा and others s Upasargas as well as Karma- ravacanīyas, do not denote any ense, but they indicate it; they re in fact द्योतक and not वाचक. or details see Nir. I. 3, Vākya- adīya II. 190, Mahābhāṣya on
' i. 3.1. Vārt. 7 and Pradīpa and ddyota thereon. The Ṛk Prā- iśākhya has discussed the gues- ion in XII. 6-9 where, as xplained by the commentator, t is stated that prefixes express a ense along with roots or nouns o which they are attached. It s not clear whether they convey he sense by denotation or indi- ation, the words वाचक in stanza


